00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:24.830
Actually, I had a friend
who's an orthopedic surgeon

00:01:24.830 --> 00:01:27.590
and is in charge of a group
of orthopedic surgeons.

00:01:27.590 --> 00:01:30.680
And he asked me to speak
to them at a dinner,

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:32.240
about the stock market.

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:34.490
And I said, OK, these
are smart, educated guys.

00:01:34.490 --> 00:01:35.840
They can understand this stuff.

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:38.092
And I spoke for
about 35 minutes,

00:01:38.092 --> 00:01:40.550
explaining how the stock market
worked and everything else.

00:01:40.550 --> 00:01:43.850
And then I started getting
questions along the lines of,

00:01:43.850 --> 00:01:45.560
oil went down $2 yesterday--

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:46.370
What should I do?

00:01:46.370 --> 00:01:48.970
Or a market was
up 2% yesterday--

00:01:48.970 --> 00:01:51.830
what do I do about that?

00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:53.830
So my interpretation
of those questions

00:01:53.830 --> 00:01:56.260
was I had just
crashed and burned.

00:01:56.260 --> 00:02:00.760
So last year, I was
lucky enough to be

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:05.800
asked to teach a ninth-grade
class, a bunch of kids,

00:02:05.800 --> 00:02:07.330
mostly from Harlem.

00:02:07.330 --> 00:02:09.070
And I had just
sort of crashed and

00:02:09.070 --> 00:02:11.380
burned with the
orthopedic surgeons,

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:13.940
and I didn't want to
do that with the kids.

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:15.670
And so I started
to try to think of,

00:02:15.670 --> 00:02:17.770
what could I do to
explain the stock

00:02:17.770 --> 00:02:20.470
market a little bit better?

00:02:20.470 --> 00:02:24.190
And so I walked into
class the first day,

00:02:24.190 --> 00:02:28.560
and I handed out a bunch
of three-by-five cards.

00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:33.750
And I brought in this jar
of jellybeans right here,

00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:36.180
and I asked--

00:02:36.180 --> 00:02:38.427
the students passed around
the jar of jellybeans.

00:02:38.427 --> 00:02:41.010
I asked them to count the rows,
do whatever they wanted to do,

00:02:41.010 --> 00:02:43.301
and write down their best
guess for how many jellybeans

00:02:43.301 --> 00:02:45.260
were in the jar.

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:46.760
I collected the
three-by-five cards,

00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:48.540
then I went around
the room, one by one,

00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:51.309
to each one of the
kids in the room.

00:02:51.309 --> 00:02:53.100
And I said, listen,
you can keep your guess

00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:54.308
or you can change your guess.

00:02:54.308 --> 00:02:55.230
That's up to you.

00:02:55.230 --> 00:02:57.240
And I went, one by
one, around the room

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:01.660
and asked people how many, and
wrote down the various guesses.

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:06.040
So it turned out, the
average of the guesses

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:10.750
for the three-by-five
cards was 1,771 jellybeans.

00:03:10.750 --> 00:03:14.410
There are 1,776
jellybeans in the jar,

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:16.040
so that was pretty good.

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:23.077
The guess when I went around the
room, that was 850 jellybeans.

00:03:23.077 --> 00:03:25.410
And I explained to them that
the stock market's actually

00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:29.680
second-guessed, because
everyone knows what they just

00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:32.140
read in the paper or what
the guy next to them said,

00:03:32.140 --> 00:03:35.080
what they saw in the
news, and are influenced

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:37.092
by everything around them.

00:03:37.092 --> 00:03:39.550
And that was the second guess,
and that's the stock market.

00:03:39.550 --> 00:03:40.930
The cold, calculating
guess, when

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:42.346
they were counting
rows and trying

00:03:42.346 --> 00:03:45.160
to figure out what
was going on, that

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:47.350
actually was the better guess--

00:03:47.350 --> 00:03:48.730
that's not the stock market.

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:51.580
But that's where I
see our opportunity.

00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:54.880
Once a year in my class
at Columbia, at least

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:58.270
for the last five, six years,
somebody raises their hand

00:03:58.270 --> 00:04:03.430
and asks a question that
goes something like this--

00:04:03.430 --> 00:04:04.900
hey, Joel, congratulations.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:07.562
You've been doing
this for 35 years,

00:04:07.562 --> 00:04:08.770
and you've had a nice record.

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:11.630
But now there are more
computers, there's more data,

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:13.330
there's more ability
to crunch numbers.

00:04:13.330 --> 00:04:16.610
And isn't the party over for us?

00:04:16.610 --> 00:04:18.320
Isn't it just more hedge funds?

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:20.200
It's just a lot
more competition.

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:22.480
Isn't the party over for us?

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:25.240
So my students are
generally second-year MBAs--

00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:28.000
I'd say average age, 27 or so.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:29.780
So I just answer it this way.

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:33.070
I tell them, let's go back to
when you learned how to read.

00:04:33.070 --> 00:04:35.620
Let's take a look at the most
followed market in the world.

00:04:35.620 --> 00:04:37.526
That would be the United States.

00:04:37.526 --> 00:04:39.400
Let's take a look at
the most followed stocks

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:41.470
within the most followed
market in the world.

00:04:41.470 --> 00:04:43.720
Those would be the
S&amp;P 500 stocks.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:45.220
Let's take a look
at what's happened

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:46.470
since you learned how to read.

00:04:46.470 --> 00:04:50.470
So I tell them, from 1997--

00:04:50.470 --> 00:04:52.800
when they were 9 or 10--

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:56.140
to 2000, the S&amp;P 500 doubled.

00:04:56.140 --> 00:04:59.020
From 2000 to 2002, it halved.

00:04:59.020 --> 00:05:01.510
From 2002 to 2007, it doubled.

00:05:01.510 --> 00:05:04.000
From 2007 to 2009, it halved.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.000
And from 2009 to today,
it's roughly tripled,

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.180
which is my way of telling them
that people are still crazy.

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:13.760
That was just the last 17 years.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:16.090
And I'm way
understating the case,

00:05:16.090 --> 00:05:18.574
because the S&amp;P 500 is
an average of 500 stocks.

00:05:18.574 --> 00:05:20.740
If you lift up the covers
and look underneath what's

00:05:20.740 --> 00:05:22.300
going on, there's
huge dispersion

00:05:22.300 --> 00:05:24.730
of those 500 stocks
between those,

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:26.950
at any particular time,
that are in favor and those

00:05:26.950 --> 00:05:28.240
that are out of favor.

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:31.220
And so there's a wild ride
going on underneath the covers.

00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:32.045
If you look under
the covers, there's

00:05:32.045 --> 00:05:34.480
a wild ride of those 500
stocks at any particular time.

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:35.770
And that doubling
and halving, doubling

00:05:35.770 --> 00:05:37.519
and halving with the
average of 500 stocks

00:05:37.519 --> 00:05:39.640
is really smoothing the ride.

00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:44.720
So there should
be an opportunity.

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:46.810
And if you understand
what stocks are--

00:05:46.810 --> 00:05:49.870
and I guarantee my students,
first day of class--

00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:51.250
I make a guarantee every year.

00:05:51.250 --> 00:05:52.833
And they walk in,
and I guarantee them

00:05:52.833 --> 00:05:57.600
this-- if they do good
valuation work of a company,

00:05:57.600 --> 00:05:59.854
I guarantee them the market
will agree with them.

00:05:59.854 --> 00:06:01.020
I just never tell them when.

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:02.145
It could be a couple weeks.

00:06:02.145 --> 00:06:03.436
It could be two or three years.

00:06:03.436 --> 00:06:05.160
But if they do good
valuation work,

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:06.630
the market will agree with them.

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:10.030
Stocks are not pieces of
paper that bounce up and down,

00:06:10.030 --> 00:06:12.390
and you put
complicated ratios on,

00:06:12.390 --> 00:06:14.610
like Sharpe ratios
or Sortino ratios.

00:06:14.610 --> 00:06:16.470
Stocks are ownership
shares of businesses

00:06:16.470 --> 00:06:18.900
that you are valuing
and, if so inclined,

00:06:18.900 --> 00:06:21.560
tried to buy at a discount.

00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:23.360
So if you believe
what Ben Graham said,

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:27.820
that this horizontal
line is fair value,

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:30.690
and this wavy line around
that horizontal line

00:06:30.690 --> 00:06:34.879
are stock prices, and you
have a disciplined process

00:06:34.879 --> 00:06:37.170
to buy, perhaps, more than
your fair share when they're

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:39.900
below the line, and,
if so inclined, sell

00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:41.370
or short more than
your fair share

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:43.110
when they're above
the line, the market

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:46.842
is throwing us pitches
all of the time.

00:06:46.842 --> 00:06:48.800
The reason people don't
outperform the market--

00:06:48.800 --> 00:06:49.800
there are behavioral problem.

00:06:49.800 --> 00:06:50.883
There are agency problems.

00:06:50.883 --> 00:06:55.110
But it's not because we're not
getting those opportunities.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:58.750
I will show you briefly--

00:06:58.750 --> 00:07:02.100
let me tell you how
we value stocks.

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:06.120
It's not very tough, and I think
most of you will understand it.

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:12.170
And I think the
best example that

00:07:12.170 --> 00:07:13.880
seems to resonate
with most people

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:16.389
is thinking about
buying a house.

00:07:16.389 --> 00:07:17.930
And to keep the
numbers simple, let's

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:20.390
say that someone is asking
$1 million for the house.

00:07:20.390 --> 00:07:22.310
They want to sell,
and your job is

00:07:22.310 --> 00:07:25.270
to figure out whether
that's a good deal or not.

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:28.320
So there's certain
questions you would ask.

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:29.790
One of the first
questions I'd ask

00:07:29.790 --> 00:07:33.979
is, well, how much rent could
I get for that thing, OK?

00:07:33.979 --> 00:07:36.520
So in other words, if I rented
out that million-dollar house,

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:38.350
how much rent would I collect?

00:07:38.350 --> 00:07:41.860
If I were going to
collect $70,000, $80,000,

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:42.970
$90,000 a year--

00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:46.120
7%, 8%, 9% yield on that house--

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:49.490
that's one way I might
go about valuing it.

00:07:49.490 --> 00:07:52.250
And what's the next
question you would ask?

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:54.019
I'm pretty sure I
know what it would be.

00:07:54.019 --> 00:07:56.060
What are the other houses
on the block going for,

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:57.710
on the block next door
and the town next door?

00:07:57.710 --> 00:07:58.626
How does this compare?

00:07:58.626 --> 00:08:00.890
How relatively cheap is
this, relative to all

00:08:00.890 --> 00:08:02.180
my current choices?

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:03.530
So that's what we do.

00:08:03.530 --> 00:08:05.060
We look at, how
relatively cheap is

00:08:05.060 --> 00:08:07.790
this business, relative to
other similar businesses,

00:08:07.790 --> 00:08:11.240
relative to a whole universe
of choices that I have?

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:12.150
We do that.

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:14.630
We also go back in
history, look at how

00:08:14.630 --> 00:08:17.750
this company or this
house has traditionally

00:08:17.750 --> 00:08:20.720
been valued, versus other
ones in the neighborhood

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:23.390
or versus other communities.

00:08:23.390 --> 00:08:24.710
And how is it being valued now?

00:08:24.710 --> 00:08:26.900
So measures of absolute
and relative value--

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:30.860
absolutely cheap
on a rental basis,

00:08:30.860 --> 00:08:33.049
relatively cheap on all
different kinds of measures

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:35.248
that make sense to you--

00:08:35.248 --> 00:08:37.039
now, you wouldn't use
any of these measures

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:38.299
all by themselves.

00:08:38.299 --> 00:08:40.599
If you just used relative
cheapness-- if some of you

00:08:40.599 --> 00:08:42.140
remember the internet
bubble, and you

00:08:42.140 --> 00:08:44.150
bought the cheapest internet
stock, that wasn't cheap.

00:08:44.150 --> 00:08:45.524
It was just cheap
relative to all

00:08:45.524 --> 00:08:48.230
the other crazy-priced
stocks at the time.

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:50.702
But we use our measures of
absolute and relative value

00:08:50.702 --> 00:08:52.410
as checks and balances
against each other

00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:54.690
to try to zero in on fair value.

00:08:54.690 --> 00:08:56.030
So when you do this--

00:08:56.030 --> 00:09:02.960
I just want to show
you a simple chart.

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:06.600
This is actually a study we did
of our valuation methodology,

00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:09.920
very similar to the way I
just said we value a house.

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:12.110
This is how we-- we looked
at the 2,000 largest

00:09:12.110 --> 00:09:15.250
companies in the US
over a 20-year period.

00:09:15.250 --> 00:09:20.150
This was 1992 to 2012, and we
ranked them on a daily basis

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:22.460
from 1 to 2,000, based
on their discount

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:25.800
to our assessment of
value, using these metrics.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:28.620
The x-axis here-- you
probably can't see it--

00:09:28.620 --> 00:09:30.579
is just a valuation percentile.

00:09:30.579 --> 00:09:33.120
All this means is if you were
in the bottom left-hand corner,

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:34.350
and you were in the
first percentile,

00:09:34.350 --> 00:09:36.308
you're the 20 companies
at any particular time,

00:09:36.308 --> 00:09:38.100
out of those 2,000,
that measure cheapest,

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:41.490
according to our measures of
absolute and relative value.

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:43.795
Go to the 99th percentile--

00:09:43.795 --> 00:09:46.170
you would be the 20 companies
that measure most expensive

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:47.610
out of those 2,000.

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:51.480
The y-axis is the year
forward return on average

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:53.010
during those 20 years.

00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:55.980
What this chart simply
says is, on average,

00:09:55.980 --> 00:09:59.482
stocks that fell in our first
percentile, the cheapest 20,

00:09:59.482 --> 00:10:01.440
averaged a one-year
forward return during those

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:03.240
20 years of 38%.

00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:05.430
Stocks that ranked in
our second percentile

00:10:05.430 --> 00:10:08.211
averaged a one-year forward
return of about 37%.

00:10:08.211 --> 00:10:10.710
And then we drop down to this
best-fit line, which we always

00:10:10.710 --> 00:10:13.450
say we don't mind missing
when we're making extra money.

00:10:13.450 --> 00:10:15.450
And then as we measure
something more expensive,

00:10:15.450 --> 00:10:18.240
the year forward return drops.

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:21.270
And if you were sitting in my
class at Columbia and I said,

00:10:21.270 --> 00:10:23.070
hey, does anyone see
a long-short strategy

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:24.600
you might pursue if
you could predict ahead

00:10:24.600 --> 00:10:26.520
of time which stocks would
do best, second best, third

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:28.104
best, in order, and
you did not say,

00:10:28.104 --> 00:10:29.520
I guess I'd buy
these guys up here

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:30.990
in the upper left-hand
corner and short

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:32.460
these guys in the bottom
right-hand corner--

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:34.230
if you didn't say that,
I'd probably throw you out

00:10:34.230 --> 00:10:36.063
of class, because it's
very straightforward.

00:10:36.063 --> 00:10:37.530
That's what you should do.

00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:39.600
And by the way,
that's what we do.

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:41.940
The important
thing to understand

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:46.690
is that stocks are ownership
shares of businesses, OK?

00:10:46.690 --> 00:10:48.700
Now, by the way,
that beautiful chart

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:52.320
I showed you with the 90% fit--

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:54.780
why doesn't everyone do this?

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:56.280
Well, unfortunately,
it doesn't look

00:10:56.280 --> 00:10:57.390
like that when you're
living through that.

00:10:57.390 --> 00:10:58.860
That's an average over 20 years.

00:10:58.860 --> 00:11:01.484
If I showed you a snippet
of three or four years,

00:11:01.484 --> 00:11:02.400
the fit would be nice.

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:05.470
It might be 0.55, 0.6,
something like that.

00:11:05.470 --> 00:11:09.419
But it's not going to be
very cooperative, right?

00:11:09.419 --> 00:11:11.460
If what we did worked
every day, and every month,

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:13.470
and every year,
everyone would do it.

00:11:13.470 --> 00:11:14.820
It would stop working--

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:19.110
but it doesn't, unfortunately.

00:11:19.110 --> 00:11:22.530
But the reason that we stick
to what we're doing even

00:11:22.530 --> 00:11:24.670
when it's not working
is that chart,

00:11:24.670 --> 00:11:26.129
meaning the way we
value companies,

00:11:26.129 --> 00:11:27.961
our measures of absolute
and relative value,

00:11:27.961 --> 00:11:30.390
are approximately how the
market values them over time.

00:11:30.390 --> 00:11:33.770
If we were, for instance,
momentum investors--

