OK, and I will tell you
that for those of you

00:11:36.446 --> 00:11:40.040
who know that
means, momentum has

00:11:40.040 --> 00:11:43.520
been studied across the
globe over the last 30, 40

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:44.750
years in the US.

00:11:44.750 --> 00:11:47.990
It's worked pretty
much everywhere--

00:11:47.990 --> 00:11:50.750
not all the time, but on average
it's worked very well over 30,

00:11:50.750 --> 00:11:56.070
40 years, and not
just in this country.

00:11:56.070 --> 00:11:58.040
But here's the problem.

00:11:58.040 --> 00:12:02.100
What if it didn't work over
the next two or three years?

00:12:02.100 --> 00:12:05.840
It could be that we
just have to be patient.

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:08.310
It works over time,
and it's cyclical.

00:12:08.310 --> 00:12:11.280
And so it's out of favor, and we
just have to stick to our guns

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:13.274
because it's something
that's worked.

00:12:13.274 --> 00:12:15.690
Or it could be, if it didn't
work in the next two or three

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:17.549
years, that the
explanation is, hey,

00:12:17.549 --> 00:12:18.840
it's not so hard to figure out.

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:20.589
A stock used to be
down here, and now it's

00:12:20.589 --> 00:12:22.230
up here-- it's
got good momentum.

00:12:22.230 --> 00:12:24.840
And with all the data, and
the ability to crunch numbers,

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:27.120
and computers, and studies
that have come out,

00:12:27.120 --> 00:12:28.680
it's a crowded trade.

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:29.910
It's degraded.

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:33.820
It's not as good
as it used to be.

00:12:33.820 --> 00:12:36.422
And if that's what happened
over the next two, three years,

00:12:36.422 --> 00:12:38.130
I would know the answer
to that question.

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:39.421
I didn't know which one it was.

00:12:39.421 --> 00:12:42.540
Should I just be patient,
or has the trade degraded?

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:45.450
But if you view stocks as
ownership shares of businesses

00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:47.350
that you value and try
to buy at a discount,

00:12:47.350 --> 00:12:49.270
and that doesn't work
for a couple of years,

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:50.895
I'm not going to
change what I'm doing.

00:12:50.895 --> 00:12:53.430
I'm not going to buy the
bottom right-hand corner,

00:12:53.430 --> 00:12:55.820
buy all the money-losers
and the companies

00:12:55.820 --> 00:12:57.570
that don't earn anything
or are trading it

00:12:57.570 --> 00:12:58.977
100 times, free cash flow.

00:12:58.977 --> 00:13:00.810
I'm not going to buy
those, even if it works

00:13:00.810 --> 00:13:04.260
in one particular year, and then
sell the ones that are cheap,

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:06.967
relative to everything,
get me high rents,

00:13:06.967 --> 00:13:07.800
and everything else.

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:10.650
I'm not going to
change my strategy,

00:13:10.650 --> 00:13:14.460
and I believe that stocks
will eventually-- not

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:17.452
right now, but eventually
people get it right.

00:13:17.452 --> 00:13:18.660
And I may have to be patient.

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:20.130
That's really what I have to do.

00:13:20.130 --> 00:13:22.740
What that chart tells me
is I'm on the right track,

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:25.200
meaning that's sort
of our true north,

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:28.680
and we just have to be
patient to get there.

00:13:28.680 --> 00:13:31.860
The reason that these simple
metrics don't get arbitraged

00:13:31.860 --> 00:13:36.600
away is-- the example I usually
use for arbitrage is, oh, you

00:13:36.600 --> 00:13:40.290
see gold in New York at $1,200,
and it's selling at London

00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:42.450
simultaneously at $1,201.

00:13:42.450 --> 00:13:44.940
Well, an arbitrageur sitting
on a trading desk someplace

00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:47.370
will see that and buy up
gold in New York at $1,200

00:13:47.370 --> 00:13:48.960
and push the price
up a little bit.

00:13:48.960 --> 00:13:51.710
He'll simultaneously sell
gold in London at $1,201,

00:13:51.710 --> 00:13:52.860
push the price down.

00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:54.960
And they'll converge
somewhere in the middle,

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:56.790
and it'll happen so
fast on a trading desk

00:13:56.790 --> 00:13:59.490
that you don't really
even get to see that.

00:13:59.490 --> 00:14:01.740
But what if I told you, you
could buy gold in New York

00:14:01.740 --> 00:14:04.060
today at $1,200, and sometime
in the next two, three years

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:04.890
you're going to
make money, but you

00:14:04.890 --> 00:14:06.973
could lose 20% of your
money while you're waiting?

00:14:06.973 --> 00:14:09.180
There's no guy sitting
on a desk anywhere that

00:14:09.180 --> 00:14:10.710
really can do that.

00:14:10.710 --> 00:14:15.130
And frankly, time horizons
are getting shorter.

00:14:15.130 --> 00:14:17.832
It used to be,
when I was younger,

00:14:17.832 --> 00:14:19.290
I used to get
quarterly statements,

00:14:19.290 --> 00:14:20.830
and most people would
throw them in the garbage.

00:14:20.830 --> 00:14:22.996
Now you can check your stock
price 30 times a minute

00:14:22.996 --> 00:14:23.790
on the internet.

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:25.800
Maybe some of you do.

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:28.680
And time horizons are
shrinking, and we're just

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:29.970
playing time arbitrage.

00:14:29.970 --> 00:14:32.880
We're being patient, buying
cheap, good businesses,

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:37.550
and waiting for the market to
recognize the value we see.

00:14:37.550 --> 00:14:40.670
But it takes some work
to value companies.

00:14:40.670 --> 00:14:43.190
And let's say you
don't want to do that.

00:14:43.190 --> 00:14:44.150
You have a day job.

00:14:44.150 --> 00:14:45.650
I guess everyone
here has a day job,

00:14:45.650 --> 00:14:47.270
so you don't want to do that.

00:14:47.270 --> 00:14:49.730
So one thing you could
do is try to find someone

00:14:49.730 --> 00:14:51.600
good to do it for you, right?

00:14:51.600 --> 00:14:53.360
I'm showing you there's
this opportunity.

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:55.760
Maybe someone can do it for you.

00:14:55.760 --> 00:14:57.200
And what you should
probably look

00:14:57.200 --> 00:14:59.360
for when you're
looking for that person

00:14:59.360 --> 00:15:05.220
is someone who has a good
investment process that

00:15:05.220 --> 00:15:08.010
makes sense to you.

00:15:08.010 --> 00:15:12.626
The problem is, for
most active managers,

00:15:12.626 --> 00:15:14.000
if you think of
their challenge--

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.600
when they're picking
an individual stock,

00:15:17.600 --> 00:15:22.760
they must think that they have
a variant hypothesis as to why

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:27.170
that stock is priced differently
than the way it should be.

00:15:27.170 --> 00:15:29.870
And I can tell you, I've been
doing this over 35 years,

00:15:29.870 --> 00:15:31.860
and it's very rare.

00:15:31.860 --> 00:15:34.970
Almost never have I
bottom-ticked a stock, bought

00:15:34.970 --> 00:15:37.310
it at the absolute bottom.

00:15:37.310 --> 00:15:40.960
So 99.9-plus
percent of the time,

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:43.460
a stock is down
after I've bought it.

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:46.940
And there are really
only two reasons why--

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:48.830
one is I was wrong.

00:15:48.830 --> 00:15:50.300
The other is I
just need more time

00:15:50.300 --> 00:15:54.040
for my thesis to play out, OK?

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:57.550
Now, as an outside
allocator, you

00:15:57.550 --> 00:16:02.161
don't really know what the
thesis for the individual stock

00:16:02.161 --> 00:16:02.660
was.

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:09.650
Even the manager himself
sometimes doesn't know.

00:16:09.650 --> 00:16:11.390
When things are
going against you,

00:16:11.390 --> 00:16:13.220
there are all kinds
of agency problems.

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:15.050
You've got people to answer to.

00:16:15.050 --> 00:16:17.570
You have behavioral issues,
just naturally-- you

00:16:17.570 --> 00:16:19.670
start to doubt yourself.

00:16:19.670 --> 00:16:22.820
It's very unclear
sometimes, even to them,

00:16:22.820 --> 00:16:25.850
what their biases are
and what they're doing.

00:16:25.850 --> 00:16:28.610
They did studies that you guys
are familiar with, probably,

00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:31.970
of why the home team
always wins in sports,

00:16:31.970 --> 00:16:34.440
or at least wins
more than it should.

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:36.950
And the original thesis
was generally, oh, they're

00:16:36.950 --> 00:16:37.700
used to the court.

00:16:37.700 --> 00:16:39.620
They slept in their own bed.

00:16:39.620 --> 00:16:43.670
The fans, they jazz them
up, whatever it might be.

00:16:43.670 --> 00:16:46.272
And when they controlled
for all these variables,

00:16:46.272 --> 00:16:48.230
the answer turned out to
be that the refs don't

00:16:48.230 --> 00:16:50.720
like to get booed, OK?

00:16:50.720 --> 00:16:55.670
So they don't think that
they're being biased.

00:16:55.670 --> 00:16:58.310
I'm sure in 99.9% of
cases, they don't, but they

00:16:58.310 --> 00:16:59.310
don't like to get booed.

00:16:59.310 --> 00:17:00.800
And so they're being
influenced by--

00:17:00.800 --> 00:17:03.091
and so there's the same
problem with an active manager.

00:17:03.091 --> 00:17:08.762
He's got agency behavioral
issues that he's not sure of.

00:17:08.762 --> 00:17:10.970
So the allocator doesn't
really understand the thesis

00:17:10.970 --> 00:17:12.410
behind each pick.

00:17:12.410 --> 00:17:16.010
It's not clear that the
manager is totally unbiased

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:19.910
when he has a variant thesis
that's going against him.

00:17:19.910 --> 00:17:22.650
And so since you
don't know the thesis

00:17:22.650 --> 00:17:25.599
as an allocator, most people--

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:29.070
all they have are the returns,
and that's what they used.

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:32.090
So in an interesting
study that came out

00:17:32.090 --> 00:17:33.842
the day after Thanksgiving--

00:17:33.842 --> 00:17:36.050
so it was interesting to
me, probably not interesting

00:17:36.050 --> 00:17:38.880
to the guys who did the study.

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:41.390
Morningstar put out a
study of their star system.

00:17:44.310 --> 00:17:46.470
And their star system is
based on past returns,

00:17:46.470 --> 00:17:49.053
letting you know who's done the
best over the last one, three,

00:17:49.053 --> 00:17:49.770
and five years.

00:17:49.770 --> 00:17:52.230
Of course, my interpretation
of their study

00:17:52.230 --> 00:17:54.810
was that our star
system doesn't work.

00:17:54.810 --> 00:17:56.610
We can't discern.

00:17:56.610 --> 00:17:58.650
The last one, three,
five years of returns

00:17:58.650 --> 00:18:02.070
has not much to do with
the next one, three, five.

00:18:02.070 --> 00:18:04.920
But that's what everyone uses.

00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:06.960
I wrote a book.

00:18:06.960 --> 00:18:07.950
I hold it up here.

00:18:07.950 --> 00:18:09.699
It's called "The Big
Secret," and I always

00:18:09.699 --> 00:18:12.345
say it's still a big secret
because no one read it.

00:18:12.345 --> 00:18:14.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:21.650
And in that book, I talked
about a few studies.

00:18:21.650 --> 00:18:26.450
Number one, it talked about
the best-performing manager.

00:18:26.450 --> 00:18:29.690
I wrote it in 2011, so it
talked about the decade

00:18:29.690 --> 00:18:33.170
2000 to 2010-- looked at the
best-performing mutual fund,

00:18:33.170 --> 00:18:37.100
a study of the best-performing
mutual fund for that decade.

00:18:37.100 --> 00:18:41.450
That fund was up 18% per year,
100% long in the US equities.

00:18:41.450 --> 00:18:43.670
The market was flat
during those 10 years,

00:18:43.670 --> 00:18:46.639
so 18% up a year is pretty good.

00:18:46.639 --> 00:18:48.680
Unfortunately, the average
investor in that fund,

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:50.900
on a dollar-weighted
basis, managed to lose 11%

00:18:50.900 --> 00:18:54.800
a year because every
time the market went up,

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:55.610
people piled in.

00:18:55.610 --> 00:18:57.020
When the market went
down, they piled out.

00:18:57.020 --> 00:18:58.490
When the fund outperformed,
they piled in.

00:18:58.490 --> 00:19:00.365
When the fund underperformed,
they piled out.

00:19:00.365 --> 00:19:03.920
And they took an 18% annual
gain and turned it into an 11%

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:07.570
annual dollar-weighted loss--

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:08.070
why?

00:19:08.070 --> 00:19:10.400
Well, to beat the market, if
you're beating by 18 points,

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:11.910
you're doing something
different than the market.

00:19:11.910 --> 00:19:13.576
You're going to zig
and zag differently.

00:19:13.576 --> 00:19:15.200
You can't do the
same as the market.

00:19:15.200 --> 00:19:16.658
You have to do
something different.

00:19:16.658 --> 00:19:18.560
You're going to zig
and zag differently.

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:20.480
Institutional managers
are no different.

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:23.900
Here are the stats on the-- if
you just took a look at the top

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:26.340
institutional managers for
that decade, the ones who--

00:19:26.340 --> 00:19:29.310
2000 to 2010-- the
top-quartile managers,

00:19:29.310 --> 00:19:31.490
the ones who ended up with
the best 10-year record,

00:19:31.490 --> 00:19:32.870
here are the stats on them.

00:19:32.870 --> 00:19:37.430
97% of those who ended up
with the best 10-year record,

00:19:37.430 --> 00:19:40.070
top quartile, spent
at least 3 of the 10

00:19:40.070 --> 00:19:41.830
years in the bottom
half of performance--

00:19:41.830 --> 00:19:43.310
not shocking, but
everyone, right?

00:19:43.310 --> 00:19:45.030
To beat the market, you have
to do something different.

00:19:45.030 --> 00:19:46.696
You're going to zig
and zag differently.

00:19:46.696 --> 00:19:49.299
79% of those who ended up
with the best 10-year record

00:19:49.299 --> 00:19:51.590
spent at least 3 of the 10
years in the bottom quartile

00:19:51.590 --> 00:19:52.700
performance.

00:19:52.700 --> 00:19:54.860
And here's the stunner--

00:19:54.860 --> 00:19:58.460
47%, roughly half of those who--
they ended up with the best

00:19:58.460 --> 00:20:01.340
record, but they spent at
least 3 of those 10 years

00:20:01.340 --> 00:20:03.680
in the bottom decile, the
bottom 10% of performers.

00:20:03.680 --> 00:20:05.480
So you know no one
stayed with them,

00:20:05.480 --> 00:20:07.570
but they ended up
with the best record.

00:20:11.520 --> 00:20:17.230
So it's very hard to
pick an allocator,

00:20:17.230 --> 00:20:18.910
because you don't
know the thesis,

00:20:18.910 --> 00:20:20.717
so you're using past returns.

00:20:20.717 --> 00:20:22.300
But when you do that,
all you're doing

00:20:22.300 --> 00:20:26.410
is chasing your tail, going in
and out at all the wrong times,

00:20:26.410 --> 00:20:29.140
So it's very hard.

00:20:29.140 --> 00:20:30.646
What a good allocator--

00:20:30.646 --> 00:20:32.520
usually an institutional
allocator, and there

00:20:32.520 --> 00:20:33.804
are a few of them--

00:20:33.804 --> 00:20:35.470
should be looking at
process, and do you

00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:36.977
stay with your process.

00:20:36.977 --> 00:20:38.560
But of course, there's
agency problems

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:41.200
on the side of those
people allocating,

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:46.217
because even if you're on a
really good investment board,

00:20:46.217 --> 00:20:48.550
and you're an allocator, and
you're head of US equities,

00:20:48.550 --> 00:20:53.560
or you're head of
alternatives or bonds,

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:56.710
or whatever it might be,
you have a benchmark.

00:20:56.710 --> 00:20:59.590
And if you haven't beaten your
benchmark for the last three

00:20:59.590 --> 00:21:01.420
years, I'm not saying
at the good places,

00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:02.620
they throw you out.

00:21:02.620 --> 00:21:06.010
But I am saying they don't
throw you a parade, OK?

00:21:06.010 --> 00:21:09.360
So it's very, very hard on that.

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:11.330
So one thing you could
do is do it yourself.

00:21:11.330 --> 00:21:13.080
And I wrote this other
book that you have,

00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:14.850
"The Little Book That
Beats the Market."

00:21:14.850 --> 00:21:17.645
And I just did a
simple formula that

00:21:17.645 --> 00:21:19.770
sort of was like the
jellybeans, counting the rows,

00:21:19.770 --> 00:21:23.850
going across, and just picking
the cheap companies to buy,

00:21:23.850 --> 00:21:24.690
very simple.

00:21:24.690 --> 00:21:27.930
And I wasn't running
outside money at that time

00:21:27.930 --> 00:21:29.882
that I wrote the book in 2005--

00:21:29.882 --> 00:21:31.590
just wrote up the very
first study we did

00:21:31.590 --> 00:21:35.520
of doing something
cheap and good.

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:37.680
Businesses just
made it pretty easy

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:40.110
for you to buy a
handful of those.

00:21:40.110 --> 00:21:43.080
And I kept getting
phone calls-- hey,

00:21:43.080 --> 00:21:44.620
could you just do this for us?

00:21:44.620 --> 00:21:47.850
And so what I did was
I set up a website

00:21:47.850 --> 00:21:49.500
that listed the top stocks.

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:54.030
It's still going around,
MagicFormulaInvesting.com.

00:21:54.030 --> 00:21:55.572
And people said,
yeah, that's fine.

00:21:55.572 --> 00:21:57.030
But could you still
do this for us?

00:21:57.030 --> 00:21:59.610
So I set up something
called formula investing.

00:21:59.610 --> 00:22:01.830
And I gave people two choices.

00:22:01.830 --> 00:22:06.670
I said, well--

00:22:06.670 --> 00:22:09.190
I sort of viewed it as a
benevolent brokerage firm.

00:22:09.190 --> 00:22:12.500
I said, listen, we'll
let you do this yourself.

00:22:12.500 --> 00:22:16.960
But you have to choose from this
top list of 30 or 50 stocks,

00:22:16.960 --> 00:22:20.064
and you have to choose
at least 20 of them, OK?

00:22:20.064 --> 00:22:21.730
Stay out of trouble,
and you're supposed

00:22:21.730 --> 00:22:23.980
to invest every quarter,
update your portfolio,

00:22:23.980 --> 00:22:26.825
and just mechanically do this.

00:22:26.825 --> 00:22:28.200
You don't have to
buy everything,

00:22:28.200 --> 00:22:31.140
but you have to buy at least 20.

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:34.200
And then the person
who was running this

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:35.910
for me said, you know what?

00:22:35.910 --> 00:22:38.580
How about you just add
a check box which said,

00:22:38.580 --> 00:22:41.820
just do this for me, just
automatically buy it.

00:22:41.820 --> 00:22:43.590
So just as an
afterthought, I said fine.

00:22:43.590 --> 00:22:45.780
We'll do that too.

00:22:45.780 --> 00:22:47.890
So we ran this for
a couple of years,

00:22:47.890 --> 00:22:49.223
and let me tell you the results.

00:22:52.170 --> 00:22:54.120
The people who chose
their own stocks

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:57.475
from the pre-approved
list of the top stocks,

00:22:57.475 --> 00:22:58.350
they did pretty well.

00:22:58.350 --> 00:23:02.070
For the two years, they
were up 59%, roughly.

00:23:02.070 --> 00:23:09.780
Unfortunately, the S&amp;P was up
62% during those two years.

00:23:09.780 --> 00:23:13.870
The automatic, just do it
for me-- that was up 84%.

