00:31:47.740 --> 00:31:50.560
JOEL GREENBLATT: Sure, so
stock investing is figuring out

00:31:50.560 --> 00:31:53.740
what a business is
worth and paying less,

00:31:53.740 --> 00:31:54.880
and so that hasn't changed.

00:31:54.880 --> 00:31:57.054
What makes a company
worth something

00:31:57.054 --> 00:31:58.720
and what makes it
cheap relative to that

00:31:58.720 --> 00:32:00.346
is pretty straightforward.

00:32:03.999 --> 00:32:06.290
That's sort of Ben Graham--
figure out what it's worth,

00:32:06.290 --> 00:32:07.790
pay a lot less,
leave a large margin

00:32:07.790 --> 00:32:10.660
of safety between those two.

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:12.940
Warren Buffett
added a little twist

00:32:12.940 --> 00:32:15.832
that made him one of the
richest people in the world.

00:32:15.832 --> 00:32:18.040
He simply said, if you can
buy a good business cheap,

00:32:18.040 --> 00:32:20.027
even better.

00:32:20.027 --> 00:32:21.610
If you read through
Buffett's letters,

00:32:21.610 --> 00:32:23.309
it's very clear what
he's looking for--

00:32:23.309 --> 00:32:24.850
first thing he's
looking for, anyway,

00:32:24.850 --> 00:32:27.100
is businesses that are in
high returns, we call it,

00:32:27.100 --> 00:32:28.595
on tangible capital.

00:32:28.595 --> 00:32:30.970
And that just means every
business needs working capital.

00:32:30.970 --> 00:32:32.590
Every business
needs fixed assets.

00:32:32.590 --> 00:32:34.423
How well does it convert
its working capital

00:32:34.423 --> 00:32:36.264
and fixed assets into earnings?

00:32:36.264 --> 00:32:38.680
So the example I used in "The
Little Book," which I really

00:32:38.680 --> 00:32:40.900
wrote to explain these kind
of concepts to my kids--

00:32:40.900 --> 00:32:42.824
I said, imagine you're
building a store,

00:32:42.824 --> 00:32:44.740
and you have to buy the
land, build the store,

00:32:44.740 --> 00:32:46.690
set up the display,
stock it with inventory.

00:32:46.690 --> 00:32:49.090
And all that cost you $400,000.

00:32:49.090 --> 00:32:51.760
And every year, the store
spins out $200,000 in profits.

00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:54.005
That's a 50% return
on tangible capital.

00:32:54.005 --> 00:32:55.380
Maybe I should
open more stores--

00:32:55.380 --> 00:32:56.920
not so many places
I can reinvest

00:32:56.920 --> 00:32:58.870
my money at those rates.

00:32:58.870 --> 00:33:00.562
Then I compared it
to another store.

00:33:00.562 --> 00:33:02.020
Remember, I wrote
this for my kids.

00:33:02.020 --> 00:33:04.030
And I called that
store Just Broccoli.

00:33:04.030 --> 00:33:05.620
It's a store that
just sells broccoli,

00:33:05.620 --> 00:33:08.935
and it's not a very good idea.

00:33:08.935 --> 00:33:11.560
Unfortunately, you still have to
buy the land, build the store,

00:33:11.560 --> 00:33:13.393
set up the display,
stock it with inventory.

00:33:13.393 --> 00:33:16.607
That's still going to
cost you roughly $400,000.

00:33:16.607 --> 00:33:18.190
But because it's
kind of a stupid idea

00:33:18.190 --> 00:33:19.689
just to sell broccoli
in your store,

00:33:19.689 --> 00:33:21.250
maybe it only earns
$10,000 a year.

00:33:21.250 --> 00:33:23.830
That's a 2 and 1/2% return
on tangible capital.

00:33:23.830 --> 00:33:26.530
And all I simply
say is, I'd much

00:33:26.530 --> 00:33:29.260
prefer to own the business
that can reinvest its money--

00:33:29.260 --> 00:33:30.910
all things being
equal, much prefer

00:33:30.910 --> 00:33:32.451
to own the business
that can reinvest

00:33:32.451 --> 00:33:34.090
its money at high
rates of return

00:33:34.090 --> 00:33:36.670
than much lower rates of return.

00:33:36.670 --> 00:33:38.470
And so that's sort
of the Buffett twist

00:33:38.470 --> 00:33:42.160
that we incorporate in the
companies that we invest in,

00:33:42.160 --> 00:33:44.260
by being very tough
on the way companies

00:33:44.260 --> 00:33:46.160
earn and spend their money.

00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:49.360
So we tend to get a
group of companies

00:33:49.360 --> 00:33:52.850
that are not only cheap, but
also deploy capital well.

00:33:52.850 --> 00:33:55.420
And that's really what
we're looking for.

00:33:55.420 --> 00:33:57.250
So we've always done that.

00:33:57.250 --> 00:34:00.550
"The Little Book" was more
of a way to systematize that.

