were 80% of our portfolio.

00:34:28.570 --> 00:34:31.457
We returned half our outside
capital after five years.

00:34:31.457 --> 00:34:32.290
SPEAKER: Five years.

00:34:32.290 --> 00:34:33.260
JOEL GREENBLATT: We returned
all our outside capital

00:34:33.260 --> 00:34:34.090
after 10 years--

00:34:34.090 --> 00:34:34.840
SPEAKER: 10 Years.

00:34:34.840 --> 00:34:36.610
JOEL GREENBLATT:
Between '85 and '94--

00:34:36.610 --> 00:34:40.210
we were lucky enough to have
enough money to keep our staff

00:34:40.210 --> 00:34:43.719
and continue to run
our money thereafter.

00:34:43.719 --> 00:34:48.320
Warren Buffett
said a fat wallet's

00:34:48.320 --> 00:34:51.739
the enemy of high
investment returns.

00:34:51.739 --> 00:34:53.929
And so when you have a very
concentrated portfolio,

00:34:53.929 --> 00:34:56.090
and you're looking off the
beaten path, where there

00:34:56.090 --> 00:34:59.054
are smaller situations and
things that are more obscure,

00:34:59.054 --> 00:35:00.470
you're very
liquidity-constrained.

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:04.610
That's why we kept
returning money,

00:35:04.610 --> 00:35:07.430
but that's not why we're
doing what we're doing now.

00:35:07.430 --> 00:35:09.750
If you're going to run
other people's money,

00:35:09.750 --> 00:35:11.750
this is what I'll tell
you with a portfolio that

00:35:11.750 --> 00:35:14.960
has 6 or 8 names that are
80% of your portfolio.

00:35:14.960 --> 00:35:20.490
Every two to three years,
usually within two, Rob and I--

00:35:20.490 --> 00:35:22.520
my partner, Rob Goldstein,
and I would wake up,

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:27.560
and we'd find out we just lost
20% or 30% of our net worth.

00:35:27.560 --> 00:35:30.020
And that happened like clockwork
every two or three years--

00:35:30.020 --> 00:35:30.850
just always happened.

00:35:30.850 --> 00:35:32.808
It has to happen with a
concentrated portfolio,

00:35:32.808 --> 00:35:37.160
either because we were wrong
on one or two of our picks,

00:35:37.160 --> 00:35:39.620
or market--

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:41.660
they were out of favor
for some period of time.

00:35:41.660 --> 00:35:43.940
And maybe it bothered us,
maybe it didn't if we just

00:35:43.940 --> 00:35:46.100
had to be patient.

00:35:46.100 --> 00:35:48.830
But I would say
for outside, when

00:35:48.830 --> 00:35:51.560
I was talking about people
going in and out of funds

00:35:51.560 --> 00:35:54.530
and losing their turn, that is
not conducive for other people,

00:35:54.530 --> 00:35:56.330
especially if they're
not doing the work.

00:35:56.330 --> 00:36:00.560
It was OK for us, and I
think it was good for us

00:36:00.560 --> 00:36:02.250
because we knew what we owned.

00:36:02.250 --> 00:36:04.640
And so as long as the facts
hadn't changed, and as long

00:36:04.640 --> 00:36:08.090
as we believed in our
thesis, we could take that.

00:36:08.090 --> 00:36:11.000
I wouldn't say it was easy,
but we could take that.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:12.796
Now, our bad days,
we have hundreds

00:36:12.796 --> 00:36:14.420
of stocks on the long
side and hundreds

00:36:14.420 --> 00:36:15.380
of stocks on the short side.

00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:16.530
We're trying to be
right on average.

00:36:16.530 --> 00:36:17.988
We're buying cheap,
good companies.

00:36:17.988 --> 00:36:19.880
We're shorting
companies that are

00:36:19.880 --> 00:36:21.920
either destroying
capital, or losing money,

00:36:21.920 --> 00:36:23.330
or whatever it is.

00:36:23.330 --> 00:36:25.580
And over time, that pays off.

00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:27.830
But our bad days, with
hundreds of stocks on the side,

00:36:27.830 --> 00:36:31.000
are 20 or 30 basis points of
under-performance, not 20%,

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:32.810
30% of our net worth.

00:36:32.810 --> 00:36:35.390
And so I think for most
people, it's a smoother ride.

00:36:35.390 --> 00:36:39.515
And one of the great lessons
that young investors--

00:36:39.515 --> 00:36:42.770
and a lot of you guys
are still very young--

00:36:42.770 --> 00:36:45.740
can learn are the
compound interest tables.

00:36:45.740 --> 00:36:47.180
If you can make
mid-teen returns--

00:36:47.180 --> 00:36:49.490
wouldn't make 40% or
50% annualized returns,

00:36:49.490 --> 00:36:53.180
but in mid-teens returns, if you
know compound interest tables,

00:36:53.180 --> 00:36:57.290
you can do very well
with a smoother ride

00:36:57.290 --> 00:36:59.550
over a long period of time.

00:36:59.550 --> 00:37:03.980
One of the best examples--
and when I taught those

00:37:03.980 --> 00:37:05.907
ninth-graders, I actually
put on the outside

00:37:05.907 --> 00:37:06.740
of their notebooks--

00:37:06.740 --> 00:37:07.610
I handed them notebooks.

00:37:07.610 --> 00:37:09.890
And I on the outside, I had
a compound interest table.

00:37:09.890 --> 00:37:16.280
And it had the example of
starting investing $2,000

00:37:16.280 --> 00:37:22.970
a year when you're 19, in
your IRA, until you're 26--

00:37:22.970 --> 00:37:25.400
so seven years of
putting away $2,000--

00:37:25.400 --> 00:37:27.920
and never putting
another nickel in again,

00:37:27.920 --> 00:37:31.010
or starting when you're
26 and putting in $2,000

00:37:31.010 --> 00:37:35.280
a year for 40 years,
until you're 65.

00:37:35.280 --> 00:37:39.380
So the people who put in
$2,000 a year from age 19 to 26

00:37:39.380 --> 00:37:42.980
and never put in another
nickel ended up with more money

00:37:42.980 --> 00:37:45.440
if you earn 10% a
year on that money.

00:37:45.440 --> 00:37:47.870
They ended up with more money
with those seven payments

00:37:47.870 --> 00:37:50.210
than the people who start at
26 and put in 40 payments,

00:37:50.210 --> 00:37:51.290
till they were 65.

00:37:51.290 --> 00:37:55.590
You end up with more
money, the 19 to 26--

00:37:55.590 --> 00:37:59.540
just a very important lesson
to learn about starting early.

00:37:59.540 --> 00:38:01.130
I know all of you
are over 19, so I'm

00:38:01.130 --> 00:38:02.338
sorry I didn't tell you this.

00:38:02.338 --> 00:38:03.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:03.620 --> 00:38:08.767
But these kids weren't, and
so compound interest tables

00:38:08.767 --> 00:38:09.350
are important.

00:38:09.350 --> 00:38:16.790
So you're young-- if you
stay with a very methodical

00:38:16.790 --> 00:38:19.940
investment strategy that
makes sense over time,

00:38:19.940 --> 00:38:22.067
you can all still
do very, very well.

00:38:22.067 --> 00:38:23.150
SPEAKER: So, Joel, thanks.

00:38:23.150 --> 00:38:25.070
You've talked about
the size effect, right?

00:38:25.070 --> 00:38:28.610
Going into hidden places
and obscure areas as well--

00:38:28.610 --> 00:38:30.560
you also talked about
the temperamental edge

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:33.920
that you can bring to
the process of investing.

00:38:33.920 --> 00:38:37.850
And then there is something
to say about the analytical

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:39.410
and the informational edge.

00:38:39.410 --> 00:38:44.600
And there used to be a lot of
investing in net nets payback.

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:47.420
And do you think
some of these edges

00:38:47.420 --> 00:38:49.910
have become less relevant,
versus more relevant,

00:38:49.910 --> 00:38:54.110
over time, with information
becoming almost universally

00:38:54.110 --> 00:38:56.580
accessible?

00:38:56.580 --> 00:38:58.850
JOEL GREENBLATT:
Well, information--

00:38:58.850 --> 00:39:02.210
people have information
on the S&amp;P 500 stocks.

00:39:02.210 --> 00:39:06.189
There's still a lot of
group-think going on.

00:39:06.189 --> 00:39:08.480
What I tell my students is,
some of these smaller cap--

00:39:08.480 --> 00:39:11.150
you know what happens if you're
very good at doing things,

00:39:11.150 --> 00:39:13.280
like you read "You Can
Be a Stock Market Genius"

00:39:13.280 --> 00:39:15.830
and buy some of these things
in these obscure places.

00:39:15.830 --> 00:39:18.260
And what I would call it
is taking unfair bets,

00:39:18.260 --> 00:39:22.220
not because you're so smart, but
because you found it in a place

00:39:22.220 --> 00:39:25.195
that other people
aren't looking.

00:39:25.195 --> 00:39:27.320
What happens to people who
get good at that is they

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:28.694
get a lot of money,
and then they

00:39:28.694 --> 00:39:31.910
can't do that anymore because
they have too much money.

00:39:31.910 --> 00:39:35.420
So it opens a whole new
area for young people

00:39:35.420 --> 00:39:37.140
to keep coming into that.

00:39:37.140 --> 00:39:39.140
So certainly, some of
the smaller situations

00:39:39.140 --> 00:39:40.015
will always be there.

00:39:42.987 --> 00:39:44.570
Things may be a
little more efficient,

00:39:44.570 --> 00:39:45.740
But there have been
plenty studies that--

00:39:45.740 --> 00:39:47.810
one of the big chapters
I wrote was on spin-offs,

00:39:47.810 --> 00:39:50.740
which are companies that
are sort of separated from--

00:39:50.740 --> 00:39:52.250
and those still work very well.

00:39:52.250 --> 00:39:53.840
But it sort of misses--

00:39:53.840 --> 00:39:55.370
they've studied, if you
bought all of the spin-offs,

00:39:55.370 --> 00:39:56.078
how would you do?

00:39:56.078 --> 00:39:57.890
And they continue to outperform.

00:39:57.890 --> 00:39:59.630
That's not really the question.

00:39:59.630 --> 00:40:04.070
The question is, is this an area
ripe for mispriced securities?

00:40:04.070 --> 00:40:06.770
If the average
spin-off did average,

00:40:06.770 --> 00:40:08.360
that wouldn't mean
anything to me.

00:40:08.360 --> 00:40:10.250
You're looking for
the opportunity

00:40:10.250 --> 00:40:11.930
where people are
discarding things

00:40:11.930 --> 00:40:13.599
or are just not
interested in things

00:40:13.599 --> 00:40:16.140
for reasons that don't have to
do with the investment merits.

00:40:16.140 --> 00:40:17.546
They may be too small.

00:40:17.546 --> 00:40:19.670
It may not be the company
that the people who owned

00:40:19.670 --> 00:40:22.850
the original stock invested in.

00:40:22.850 --> 00:40:26.750
Usually, you discard companies
that are out of favor

00:40:26.750 --> 00:40:27.630
at that time.

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:29.120
So even though on
average, they've

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:30.950
continued to outperform
pretty much as

00:40:30.950 --> 00:40:32.405
well as when I wrote the book--

00:40:32.405 --> 00:40:33.530
so that's not discouraging.

00:40:33.530 --> 00:40:36.260
But even if they did
average, they still

00:40:36.260 --> 00:40:39.110
are ripe for mispricing,
really what I'm looking for.

00:40:39.110 --> 00:40:42.040
So you're looking in these areas
that are ripe for mispricing.

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:44.330
You don't have to run a
statistical model to decide

00:40:44.330 --> 00:40:46.970
whether, on average, they
do well or they don't.

00:40:46.970 --> 00:40:48.570
If you know what
you're looking for,

00:40:48.570 --> 00:40:50.630
you're looking for
opportunities to find

00:40:50.630 --> 00:40:51.810
things that are mispriced.

00:40:51.810 --> 00:40:55.550
And I don't think
those will go away.

00:40:55.550 --> 00:40:59.390
But as I said, there are
higher and better uses

00:40:59.390 --> 00:41:01.490
for most people's time.

00:41:01.490 --> 00:41:03.040
So I had a ball doing that.

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:04.520
I have a ball doing
what I'm doing.

00:41:04.520 --> 00:41:06.680
If you don't want to
do it, fine with me.

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:09.320
SPEAKER: In one of
your recent interviews,

00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:12.590
I think you mentioned Apple,
one of the big companies.

00:41:12.590 --> 00:41:15.830
And you think group think and
mispricings can happen even

00:41:15.830 --> 00:41:16.670
in big companies.

00:41:16.670 --> 00:41:19.190
So maybe Apple or
some other company--

00:41:19.190 --> 00:41:21.290
I was wondering if you
could take our audience

00:41:21.290 --> 00:41:23.810
through an example of,
what are the metrics one

00:41:23.810 --> 00:41:27.440
should be looking at if they
were looking at a company?

00:41:27.440 --> 00:41:30.500
JOEL GREENBLATT: Well, I'll pick
Apple as just big, big picture.

00:41:30.500 --> 00:41:31.786
You guys have heard of that?

00:41:31.786 --> 00:41:32.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:32.700 --> 00:41:41.630
So at least I'm old enough
to have had a BlackBerry.

00:41:41.630 --> 00:41:46.504
And it used to have
50% of the market.

00:41:46.504 --> 00:41:47.670
Now it doesn't really exist.

00:41:47.670 --> 00:41:48.780
It wasn't that long ago.

00:41:51.980 --> 00:41:56.636
And the vast majority of Apple's
profits come from their phone.

00:41:56.636 --> 00:41:58.260
So that's the negative
story on Apple--

00:41:58.260 --> 00:41:59.260
it's a hardware company.

00:41:59.260 --> 00:42:02.830
It's going to crash and burn
like all of them do, OK?

00:42:02.830 --> 00:42:06.850
On the other hand, some
people might say, oh,

00:42:06.850 --> 00:42:10.540
it has an ecosystem of products
that play off one another.

00:42:10.540 --> 00:42:11.890
They interact with one another.

00:42:11.890 --> 00:42:13.000
It has a brand.

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:15.430
I always say, hey, Coca-Cola
doesn't make sugar water,

00:42:15.430 --> 00:42:18.730
and they have kept
their brand pretty well.

00:42:18.730 --> 00:42:20.950
People tend to like
Apple as a brand.

00:42:20.950 --> 00:42:26.040
And so the question
is, which is it?

00:42:26.040 --> 00:42:28.510
Is Apple a hardware
company, or is it

00:42:28.510 --> 00:42:32.020
an ecosystem of products
with a great brand name?

00:42:32.020 --> 00:42:34.907
I'd say the answer is probably
gray, somewhere in between.

00:42:34.907 --> 00:42:35.740
It's not either one.

00:42:35.740 --> 00:42:37.660
It's probably somewhere
in between those two.

00:42:41.034 --> 00:42:46.790
But if you took a
look at the market,

00:42:46.790 --> 00:42:48.970
I can look at where
the S&amp;P is trading.

00:42:48.970 --> 00:42:52.510
I can look where
Apple's trading.

00:42:52.510 --> 00:42:56.830
And a few months ago--
it's still very cheap,

00:42:56.830 --> 00:42:59.110
but a few months ago, it was
trading at less than half

00:42:59.110 --> 00:43:03.970
of the valuation of
the S&amp;P. So at a price,

00:43:03.970 --> 00:43:06.490
my answer is, if it's
somewhere in between,

00:43:06.490 --> 00:43:08.320
I'd say it's probably
better than average.

00:43:08.320 --> 00:43:10.402
And I'm getting
it at half price.

00:43:10.402 --> 00:43:11.860
I don't know if
that's right, but I

00:43:11.860 --> 00:43:13.900
have a large margin of safety.

00:43:13.900 --> 00:43:15.610
I own hundreds of--

00:43:15.610 --> 00:43:17.472
what I say is,
what we do now is,

00:43:17.472 --> 00:43:19.180
I don't know the answer
to your question.

00:43:19.180 --> 00:43:19.951
It's gray.

00:43:19.951 --> 00:43:20.950
I don't know the answer.

00:43:20.950 --> 00:43:23.033
I don't know if it's closer
to a hardware company.

00:43:23.033 --> 00:43:26.560
I don't know if it's a
ecosystem with a brand attached,

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:29.440
and so it's much, much better.

00:43:29.440 --> 00:43:32.510
But interest rates are 2%.

00:43:32.510 --> 00:43:34.270
It's got a 10% free
cash flow yields,

00:43:34.270 --> 00:43:35.710
earns high returns on capital.

00:43:35.710 --> 00:43:37.270
It's got a great niche.

00:43:37.270 --> 00:43:41.380
What I would say is, I don't
know if Apple's going to work,

00:43:41.380 --> 00:43:42.580
but I don't own just Apple.

00:43:42.580 --> 00:43:44.340
I own a bucket of Apples.

00:43:44.340 --> 00:43:46.390
I own a bucket of
companies with metrics

00:43:46.390 --> 00:43:50.980
like that-- trading really
cheap, with deploys capital

00:43:50.980 --> 00:43:54.895
well, with nice
potential prospects.

00:43:54.895 --> 00:43:56.770
And so I don't know if
Apple's going to work.

00:43:56.770 --> 00:43:58.900
I know my bucket of
Apples is going to work.

00:43:58.900 --> 00:44:00.470
That was the chart I showed you.

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:02.890
And so we own the
bucket of Apples.

00:44:02.890 --> 00:44:04.690
But if you ask my
bet on Apple, I

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:09.980
think it's cheap, relative
to other choices right now.

00:44:09.980 --> 00:44:12.230
SPEAKER: Fantastic, I just
have a couple of questions,

00:44:12.230 --> 00:44:14.030
Joel, quickly.

00:44:14.030 --> 00:44:17.300
You mentioned index fund in
the beginning of your talk.

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:19.960
With all the money flowing
into passive funds, ETFs,

00:44:19.960 --> 00:44:23.060
and index funds, what would
be your contrarian moves

00:44:23.060 --> 00:44:25.544
during a period like that?

00:44:25.544 --> 00:44:27.710
Are there things investors
should be cautious about,

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:29.605
for example?

00:44:29.605 --> 00:44:30.980
JOEL GREENBLATT:
Well, I told you

00:44:30.980 --> 00:44:32.810
where I thought the
market in general--

00:44:32.810 --> 00:44:38.250
it's a market cap weighted
index, S&amp;P 500 was expensive,

00:44:38.250 --> 00:44:40.792
but still expecting positive
returns going forward.

00:44:40.792 --> 00:44:42.000
It's a world of alternatives.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:47.340
So the question is, how
should I invest my money?

00:44:51.600 --> 00:44:56.470
The move to passive can, with
all the ETFs and everything

00:44:56.470 --> 00:44:59.620
else, can cause dislocations
in the short term,

00:44:59.620 --> 00:45:03.220
because people are
not discerning.

00:45:03.220 --> 00:45:05.785
Remember, I said stocks
are not pieces of paper

00:45:05.785 --> 00:45:08.410
that bounce around, that you put
Sharpe ratios and Sortinos on.

00:45:08.410 --> 00:45:12.910
They're ownership shares of
businesses, and businesses--

00:45:12.910 --> 00:45:17.410
there's a dispersion in their
fundamentals, how one is doing,

00:45:17.410 --> 00:45:18.550
versus another.

00:45:18.550 --> 00:45:21.820
When you just take
an ETF and don't

00:45:21.820 --> 00:45:25.330
discern between the differences
in the fundamentals,

00:45:25.330 --> 00:45:28.850
that can cause dislocations
in the short term.

00:45:28.850 --> 00:45:32.140
That just makes me smile more
because those dislocations

00:45:32.140 --> 00:45:34.300
mean, hey, I can find
bargains because people

00:45:34.300 --> 00:45:36.070
stopped thinking.

00:45:36.070 --> 00:45:38.230
But I don't think they're
at such an extent,

00:45:38.230 --> 00:45:39.470
other than in the short term.

00:45:39.470 --> 00:45:41.470
I think you're familiar--
when the market falls,

00:45:41.470 --> 00:45:43.810
and everyone gets
depressed all at once,

00:45:43.810 --> 00:45:45.220
they say correlations go to 1.

00:45:45.220 --> 00:45:46.810
That just means everyone
throws the baby out

00:45:46.810 --> 00:45:47.601
with the bathwater.

00:45:47.601 --> 00:45:48.980
They make no discernment.

00:45:48.980 --> 00:45:52.000
But that really just happens
for the first month, maybe two

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:52.524
at the most.

00:45:52.524 --> 00:45:54.190
And then there starts
to be discernment.

00:45:54.190 --> 00:45:57.010
That's actually the best
opportunity time for us,

00:45:57.010 --> 00:45:58.480
when people start
discerning again.

00:45:58.480 --> 00:46:01.330
And you just had everything move
together, which it shouldn't.

00:46:01.330 --> 00:46:03.820
They all have
different prospects.

00:46:03.820 --> 00:46:06.250
And so the same with
ETFs, if there's flows

00:46:06.250 --> 00:46:09.130
into them or the indexes--

00:46:09.130 --> 00:46:12.790
that could cause
short-term dislocations

00:46:12.790 --> 00:46:16.450
over a month or two, but
those get corrected over time.

00:46:16.450 --> 00:46:21.100
Like I said, the market
eventually gets it right.

00:46:21.100 --> 00:46:22.442
There's a lot of--

00:46:22.442 --> 00:46:23.650
just think of the jellybeans.

00:46:23.650 --> 00:46:24.480
You really get it.

00:46:24.480 --> 00:46:27.579
It's the jellybean effect
of when everyone hears

00:46:27.579 --> 00:46:28.870
what everyone else is thinking.

00:46:28.870 --> 00:46:30.470
That happens most of the time.

00:46:30.470 --> 00:46:32.710
That's what the stock market is.

00:46:32.710 --> 00:46:36.970
Your job is to be cold and
calculating and unemotional.

00:46:36.970 --> 00:46:39.640
Unfortunately, people are human.

00:46:39.640 --> 00:46:46.000
It's good news for
us, but people--

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:47.950
the stats are against you.

00:46:47.950 --> 00:46:52.510
That's why I think
the indexers get

00:46:52.510 --> 00:46:54.892
it right for the wrong reasons.

00:46:54.892 --> 00:46:56.350
They mostly are
saying the market's

00:46:56.350 --> 00:46:59.410
efficient and have other
explanations of why

00:46:59.410 --> 00:47:00.220
you can't beat it.

00:47:00.220 --> 00:47:03.400
I think the market often
gives you opportunities,

00:47:03.400 --> 00:47:06.010
but it's very difficult
to take advantage of them

00:47:06.010 --> 00:47:09.300
for behavioral and
agency problems.

00:47:09.300 --> 00:47:11.230
And those are much
more powerful than you

00:47:11.230 --> 00:47:14.680
would think by just saying, oh,
behavioral and agency problems.

00:47:14.680 --> 00:47:18.644
The people are people, and
it's been happening forever.

00:47:18.644 --> 00:47:20.060
I don't think it's
getting better.

00:47:20.060 --> 00:47:23.950
I think time horizons
are shortening.

00:47:23.950 --> 00:47:28.210
There's so much-- all that
data, all that-- look,

00:47:28.210 --> 00:47:30.544
when I started my
first firm in 1985,

00:47:30.544 --> 00:47:31.960
I used to write
quarterly letters.

00:47:31.960 --> 00:47:34.930
And they read
something like this--

00:47:34.930 --> 00:47:37.330
we were up 3% last
quarter, thanks a lot.

00:47:37.330 --> 00:47:39.880
That's what it sort of said.

00:47:39.880 --> 00:47:43.630
Now we have $10 and $20
billion endowments that

00:47:43.630 --> 00:47:46.961
need to get our results weekly.

00:47:46.961 --> 00:47:48.460
I don't know what
they do with them.

00:47:48.460 --> 00:47:50.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:50.850 --> 00:47:56.654
But we now have to do
that, and most of them

00:47:56.654 --> 00:47:57.570
do a good job with it.

00:47:57.570 --> 00:47:59.565
But that's just the
way of the world.

00:47:59.565 --> 00:48:01.690
So if you keep measuring
things in shorter periods,

00:48:01.690 --> 00:48:03.690
and you can measure them,
and there's more data,

00:48:03.690 --> 00:48:05.440
it doesn't make it better.

00:48:05.440 --> 00:48:08.869
It makes you more susceptible
to emotional influence.

00:48:08.869 --> 00:48:10.160
So that world's getting better.

00:48:10.160 --> 00:48:13.270
The last man
standing is patience.

00:48:13.270 --> 00:48:15.130
We call it time arbitrage.

00:48:15.130 --> 00:48:17.950
Other people call it time
arbitrage-- just being patient.

00:48:17.950 --> 00:48:23.230
That's in really short supply,
and it's not getting better.

00:48:23.230 --> 00:48:26.870
Things are moving to
faster and less patience.

00:48:26.870 --> 00:48:29.044
So that's really the secret.

00:48:29.044 --> 00:48:30.460
So now you don't
have to even read

00:48:30.460 --> 00:48:32.750
the big secret [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:32.750 --> 00:48:35.080
SPEAKER: I think one
fantastic gift you've

