00:50:29.620 --> 00:50:30.620
you have to be a member.

00:50:30.620 --> 00:50:34.967
So learn how to value a
business and apply, if you like.

00:50:34.967 --> 00:50:36.550
There are instructions
on the website.

00:50:36.550 --> 00:50:38.091
It's called the
Value Investors Club.

00:50:38.091 --> 00:50:40.810
But as a learning tool, I
always refer people there

00:50:40.810 --> 00:50:43.840
because these are
very smart investors.

00:50:43.840 --> 00:50:45.130
They beat each other up.

00:50:45.130 --> 00:50:47.564
There's a Q&amp;A after they
post something, and say,

00:50:47.564 --> 00:50:48.230
what about this?

00:50:48.230 --> 00:50:49.520
What about that?

00:50:49.520 --> 00:50:52.240
A great rating out of 10
is 5, because everyone's

00:50:52.240 --> 00:50:55.000
mean and very--

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:56.000
they're value investors.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:58.420
They're very tough and stingy.

00:50:58.420 --> 00:50:59.550
And so they don't--

00:50:59.550 --> 00:51:04.450
so if you look at the ratings
and see anything a 5 or above,

00:51:04.450 --> 00:51:06.880
that's good, these guys.

00:51:06.880 --> 00:51:08.499
And you can look at that.

00:51:08.499 --> 00:51:10.040
It's just a learning
exercise, right?

00:51:10.040 --> 00:51:11.350
It's teach a man to fish.

00:51:11.350 --> 00:51:15.040
That's really how to
be good at investing.

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:16.789
It's not anything else.

00:51:16.789 --> 00:51:18.580
You've got to understand
what you're doing.

00:51:18.580 --> 00:51:20.100
It's a great way to learn.

00:51:20.100 --> 00:51:23.330
So I think for the
next generation,

00:51:23.330 --> 00:51:25.280
it's a nice way to
teach them to look

00:51:25.280 --> 00:51:27.200
at what smart investors
are doing now--

00:51:27.200 --> 00:51:29.241
doesn't mean I agree with
everything on the site.

00:51:32.310 --> 00:51:33.900
And this is a good point.

00:51:33.900 --> 00:51:40.480
I'm probably wrong more than I'm
right about passing on things.

00:51:40.480 --> 00:51:48.404
But Warren Buffett calls it no
called strikes on Wall Street.

00:51:48.404 --> 00:51:50.070
You could let 100
pitches go by, and you

00:51:50.070 --> 00:51:51.320
should've swung at 30 of them.

00:51:51.320 --> 00:51:52.800
But if you only
pick one, and you

00:51:52.800 --> 00:51:56.910
make sure that's a good
one, that's really the way

00:51:56.910 --> 00:51:58.200
that we go about investing.

00:51:58.200 --> 00:51:59.430
I just have to--

00:51:59.430 --> 00:52:02.700
my partner Rob Goldstein and I
are very tough on each other.

00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:04.620
So we both have to like it.

00:52:04.620 --> 00:52:06.540
We both have to
argue our points.

00:52:06.540 --> 00:52:10.930
And if we both like it,
we think it's pretty good.

00:52:10.930 --> 00:52:13.650
So we're really, really
picking our pitches.

00:52:13.650 --> 00:52:16.380
It doesn't mean we don't
miss a lot of good ones.

00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:17.850
It doesn't matter
if we miss them.

00:52:17.850 --> 00:52:19.890
It just matters the
one we pick are good.

00:52:19.890 --> 00:52:21.450
And that's sort of
the way to think

00:52:21.450 --> 00:52:25.860
about "You Can Be a Stock Market
Genius" type of investing.

00:52:25.860 --> 00:52:28.200
What we're doing now in
our long-short portfolios

00:52:28.200 --> 00:52:29.910
is more being right on average.

00:52:29.910 --> 00:52:31.230
I showed you that chart
where we're pretty

00:52:31.230 --> 00:52:32.354
good at valuing businesses.

00:52:32.354 --> 00:52:34.170
So we buy a group
of businesses where

00:52:34.170 --> 00:52:36.480
we have a bucket of Apples.

00:52:36.480 --> 00:52:39.270
And we're short a bucket
of high-priced companies.

00:52:39.270 --> 00:52:45.970
We're going to be short
some things that lose money,

00:52:45.970 --> 00:52:48.550
or the Teslas and Amazons of
the world, who are selling

00:52:48.550 --> 00:52:51.150
at 100 times free cash flow.

00:52:51.150 --> 00:52:53.500
And people get confused,
because I call that

00:52:53.500 --> 00:52:54.810
the tyranny of the anecdote.

00:52:54.810 --> 00:52:58.467
It's we will short
some wrong ones.

00:52:58.467 --> 00:53:00.550
We won't short much of
them, but we'll short some,

00:53:00.550 --> 00:53:01.480
and we'll be wrong.

00:53:01.480 --> 00:53:04.950
And you'll know their names
because those were the winners.

00:53:04.950 --> 00:53:07.630
But if you're short
hundreds, take my word.

00:53:07.630 --> 00:53:09.690
It's not a good idea
to eat through cash,

00:53:09.690 --> 00:53:13.650
or lose money, or sell at
100 times free cash flow.

00:53:13.650 --> 00:53:16.260
And usually, if you're
generating lots of cash,

00:53:16.260 --> 00:53:17.927
and you can buy that
cheap, and they're

00:53:17.927 --> 00:53:20.260
deploying their capital well,
that's a good thing to do.

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:22.290
And so we're just trying
to be right on average.

00:53:22.290 --> 00:53:24.000
Two different ways to
do it, doesn't make

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:26.670
one better than the other--

00:53:26.670 --> 00:53:32.760
there are different
ways to make money.

00:53:32.760 --> 00:53:35.970
I love them both,
would do both again.

00:53:35.970 --> 00:53:37.744
They're just both
full-time jobs.

00:53:37.744 --> 00:53:39.660
SPEAKER: Great-- and,
